04680nam a22006975i 9780801465840DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014658407 a10.7591/97808014658402doi  a(DE-B1597)515854  a(OCoLC)1048346556  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4309732231 aKirshner, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHollywood's Last Golden Age :bPolitics, Society, and the Seventies Film in America /cJonathan Kirshner. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b20 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tPROLOGUE -- tCHAPTER 1. BEFORE THE FLOOD -- tCHAPTER 2. TALKIN’ ’BOUT MY GENERATION -- tCHAPTER 3. 1968, NIXON TURN -- tCHAPTER 4. THE PERSONAL IS POLITICAL -- tCHAPTER 5. CRUMBLING CITIES AND REVISIONIST HISTORY -- tCHAPTER 6. PRIVACY, PARANOIA, DISILLUSION, AND BETRAYAL -- tCHAPTER 7. WHITE KNIGHTS IN EXISTENTIAL DESPAIR -- tCHAPTER 8. BUSINESSMEN DRINK MY WINE -- tAPPENDIX: 100 SEVENTIES FILMS OF THE LAST GOLDEN AGE -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1967 and 1976 a number of extraordinary factors converged to produce an uncommonly adventurous era in the history of American film. The end of censorship, the decline of the studio system, economic changes in the industry, and demographic shifts among audiences, filmmakers, and critics created an unprecedented opportunity for a new type of Hollywood movie, one that Jonathan Kirshner identifies as the "seventies film." In Hollywood's Last Golden Age, Kirshner shows the ways in which key films from this period—including Chinatown, Five Easy Pieces, The Graduate, and Nashville, as well as underappreciated films such as The Friends of Eddie Coyle, Klute, and Night Moves—were important works of art in continuous dialogue with the political, social, personal, and philosophical issues of their times.These "seventies films" reflected the era's social and political upheavals: the civil rights movement, the domestic consequences of the Vietnam war, the sexual revolution, women's liberation, the end of the long postwar economic boom, the Shakespearean saga of the Nixon Administration and Watergate. Hollywood films, in this brief, exceptional moment, embraced a new aesthetic and a new approach to storytelling, creating self-consciously gritty, character-driven explorations of moral and narrative ambiguity. Although the rise of the blockbuster in the second half of the 1970s largely ended Hollywood’s embrace of more challenging films, Kirshner argues that seventies filmmakers showed that it was possible to combine commercial entertainment with serious explorations of politics, society, and characters’ interior lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aFilm. 4aU.S. History. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146584040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801465840423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801465840/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK